,Not Recommended,227480,14229095,"Posted: 29 January, 2015",all,fuck off,"Hello there. Now I usually don't write detailed reviews, but I thought that I needed to get my opinion out there. This game, God Mode has a pretty interesting story. You are a descendant of a god that was banished from the heavens, and now to prove yourself worthy of becoming a god again, you must fight wave after wave of enemies set in a greek mythological world. Let's get into this.Right off the bat, there's no introduction. It pulls you up to a menu with options to create a match, join one, etc.I decided to create a match to test whether or not the game was actually fun.So I spawned in with my SMG and double barrel and walked to where I thought was the destination I had to go to, as the game did not tell me where or how I was supposed to go.I get to the location and found myself surrounded in a wide open room of skeletons. Classic, I thought.Shooting and moving being the only thing I knew how to do, I tried to survive. Any control tutorial was non-existent.After 30 seconds I was dead.I looked in the controls and found that sprint was space, melee was right click and ADS (aiming down sights) was E, not to mention that the sensitivity for the mouse was extremely high.As an average PC gamer, I can confirm that those controls are completely ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥.After changing them to my preferred buttons I continued the game, might I remind you that you have 3 lives and while I was changing these settings I was getting slaughtered without consent, listening to my character moan and bleed.With one life left I managed to kill 10 skeletons and then get brutally ripped apart by a gigantic fat guy.It wasn't pretty.I decided to restart the match and change up my tactics a little bit.All I did was run around the map, firing a clip behind me then collecting ammo/meds and running again.And then when I had killed everything and was waiting to traverse to the next area, I found myself stuck.I saw that the problem was that there was skeleton archers atop a bridge far frome my reach. Trying to shoot them proved it to be nearly impossible without wasting every single bullet I had, as the accuracy on the SMG was absolute ****.After killing them I finally got to move to the next stage, which was pretty much the same thing with a slightly different layout. I died on that stage.Determined to see what else this game had and to give it another shot I tried multiplayer, and to my surprise I actually found another player. Confused, lost and newby, but I found another player!We played the same level I was having difficulty on and managed to get to the second to last stage.During each stage, there is a modifier that changes up gameplay, and the modifier switches upon getting to the next stage. Some are good and some are bad.During my gameplay with this other player on the second to last level, we got a modifier that was meant to be extremely OP, but in turn was a game breaker.Every minute or so, one of the players would get a graphically pleasing and high-damage hammer of the gods, that after another minute would switch to the next player.Both me and him found this hammer extremely under powered, as it hit slow as anything, and only one-hit the weakling skeletons that are usually a 5 shot with your ol' SMG, not to mention that you can't run with this hammer, making fighting harder, bigger, faster foes more difficult. The most difficult to fight was the ranged enemies, as they would run and strafe-fire at you, making fighting them with the hammer completely impossible.That was the level we died on.I really think that the devs of this game, in the beginning of development, had everything going for them. A half-fresh game idea, lots of time, etc. But the direction they took it made the game absolutely horrid. To sum everything up, here are some pros and cons:Pros:Great graphicsDecent level designNo pay-to-winLots of customizationCons:Dead matchmakingExtremely boring farm/grindExtremely difficult as a beginnerBland weaponsBland upgradesCustomization options are all the same with slight differencesThank you for reading this! This was my first in-depth review! Please leave feedback"
